{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585421"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:11:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:11:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14970"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14970"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.21,0.72,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116474"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7658"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6978"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18729"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116474"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the largest single lymphoid organ in the human body?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver","Thymus","Spleen","Pancreas","Lymph node"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espleen\u003C/strong\u003E is the largest single lymphoid organ in the body, located in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen. It normally measures approximately 12 cm in length and weighs about 150g in adults. The spleen plays crucial roles in both immunity and haematological function, including the removal of aged red blood cells, storage of platelets, and immune surveillance of blood-borne pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E, while larger than the spleen, is not primarily a lymphoid organ. It is the largest internal organ and has important metabolic, synthetic, and detoxification functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethymus\u003C/strong\u003E is a lymphoid organ located in the anterior mediastinum. It is largest during childhood and typically undergoes involution during puberty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily an endocrine and exocrine organ located in the retroperitoneum. While it contains some lymphoid tissue, this is not its primary function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elymph node\u003C/strong\u003E is much smaller than the spleen, typically measuring only a few millimetres in diameter. While lymph nodes are part of the lymphatic system, they are distributed throughout the body rather than being a single organ.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The spleen is the largest single lymphoid organ in the body and plays important roles in immunity and blood cell recycling.","The spleen\u0027s normal size is approximately 12 cm in length and weighs 150g in adults.","The spleen\u0027s functions include removal of aged red blood cells, storage of platelets, and immune surveillance of blood-borne pathogens."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cesta MF. Normal structure, function, and histology of the spleen. Toxicol Pathol. 2006;34(5):455-65.